        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Έκλεκτίκη, <!-- CG: I think the diacritic should fall on the last letter: Έκλεκτικὴ -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                <!-- JE: could someone translate this please? --> 
                <!-- CG: I did some digging around and the precise usage of this word is still unclear to me. 
                    It can either reference to an "eclectic" philisophical approach, or it could be used in its more
                    literal meaning, something like "selective." 
                    Perhaps we could just translate it simply as 'Eclectic' and let other people figure it out? 
                    I also looked for the usage in Diogenes, and he uses this word primarily to describe a
                    particular philosophical school, which he refers to as "an eklektike hairesis" - which would be
                    closer to "eclectic." I suggest we go with that then. -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        apud Laertium.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Diogenes Laertius"/>
                    <!-- CG: We could also perhaps X-ref this to Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Eminent Philosophers, 1.21
                        which seems to be the sole place where he uses this word. -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                in Diogenes Laertius.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Εκλεκϒίκη. <!-- CG: I think it's still Eκλεκτίκὴ, although Harvey is getting fancy with his tau. -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                <!-- JE: Again, if someone could translate this, that would be terrific. -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Is ver&egrave; Sapiens, qui Vtilia, no qui multa scit. E gra[e]co &AElig;schyli.
                        Apollinis Oraculu[m] jubet, Ex omnibus optima eligere: et Vetus Sapientia, tota erat Gnomica, et Aphoristica.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Aeschylus"/>
                    <person name="Apollo"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The wise man is he who knows useful things, rather than many things. From the Greek of Aeschylus.
                He orders the oracle of Apollo to choose the best of all things. And old wisdom was wholly gnomic and aphoristic.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
